   {:e #blake3 "1a4d6ab3bad5f89c0a4e38ac9c8eaaf48dfb7ab4f8f5f357bf806f2bbcf42a19" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "Session entity: :recon/trace-3bf2fa6f0ecef44f; Session entity: :recon/trace-db66daa95077a8e8; Session entity: :recon/trace-7b99943734a5a0a9; Session entity: :task/t-3f9dbdb1; Session entity: :task/t-3dac54cc; Session entity: :task/t-93150b12; Session entity: :task/t-5b150bf8; Session entity: :task/t-1ea761a8; Session entity: :task/t-d23ba87d; Session entity: :recon/trace-9c69fae205a52a88; Session entity: :recon/trace-0f84f77b2710fb27; Session entity: :task/t-40843017; Session entity: :task/t-09716b50; Session entity: :recon/trace-e237f8b172bc39cd; Session entity: :recon/trace-54025146a3e3036b; Session entity: :task/t-b15000d6; Session entity: :recon/trace-e9f29300dc6b7d1d\nSPEC GAP: No spec element governs embedding model management, embedder selection, or embedder consistency across commands. The embedding module (CCE-1) has informal invariants INV-EMBEDDING-001 (determinism), INV-EMBEDDING-002 (normalization), INV-EMBEDDING-003 (graceful degradation) documented in doc comments but these are not formal spec elements in spec/. Additionally, the critical invariant discovered during DOGFOOD-3 — that all datoms in a store must use embeddings from the same vector space — has no spec element at all. NEEDED SPEC ADDITIONS: (1) INV-EMBEDDING-004: Vector space consistency — all embedding datoms in a store MUST be produced by the same embedder type. Mixed vector spaces produce meaningless cosine similarity. Falsification: any store containing embedding datoms from both HashEmbedder and Embedder without a re-embedding migration step. (2) ADR-EMBEDDING-001: Model management — model files stored at ~/.braid/models/, explicit download command, no auto-download, CLI-layer IO only (C8). (3) ADR-EMBEDDING-002: Embedder selection — prefer model2vec when available, hash fallback, re-embed innate concepts on embedder type change.; CCE-GATE ROOT CAUSE: The hash embedder (HashEmbedder) cannot bridge the semantic gap between natural agent observations and innate concept descriptions. Example: 'cascade module has five ignored error returns from Exec calls' shares ZERO keywords with the anomalies innate concept description 'Deviations from expectations — bugs, inconsistencies, violations, surprises, gaps'. The hash embedder tokenizes to words >= 3 chars and computes cosine from word overlap. For concept assignment to fire (JOIN_THRESHOLD=0.65), ~65% of words must overlap. In the DOGFOOD-3 evaluation, 30 real observations across 3 agents produced 0 concept assignments, 0 concept-mediated connections, 0 surprise-scaled responses, and 0 steering questions using concept names. The entire CCE pipeline (CCE-1 through CCE-5) was architecturally validated by 76 unit tests + 5 E2E checks, but the hash embedder fallback is insufficient for production use. The model2vec/potion-base-8M embedding model (256-dim, 30.2MB safetensors + 684KB tokenizer) was designed in CCE-1 as the primary embedding strategy, with hash embedder as graceful degradation. The model loading infrastructure (Embedder::from_bytes) exists in the kernel behind feature gate 'embeddings', but the CLI never loads model files. This is the single blocking gap between the validated architecture and production concept crystallization.; INNATE-QUALITY PROPOSAL: The innate concept descriptions were written for human readability, not embedding quality. The description 'Deviations from expectations — bugs, inconsistencies, violations, surprises, gaps' is accurate but may not produce optimal embeddings because the emdash-separated synonym list is unusual phrasing. APPROACH: After model2vec integration, test whether the current descriptions produce good embeddings by measuring cosine against realistic observations. If not, revise descriptions to be more natural-language — e.g., 'Unexpected behavior, bugs, errors, and deviations from how the system should work.' The descriptions only matter for their EMBEDDINGS, not for display (concept names are separate). ALSO: The HashEmbedder creates innate embeddings from the description text, but model2vec may produce better embeddings from a combination of name + description. Consider embedding '{name}: {description}' instead of just description. VERIFICATION: (A) Each innate concept matches >= 3 of the 30 DOGFOOD observations with cosine > threshold. (B) No innate concept matches < 1 observation (dead schema). (C) No observation matches more than 2 innate concepts above threshold (schema ambiguity).; EMBEDDER-CONSISTENCY PROPOSAL: The embedding vector space must be consistent across all datom-producing commands. Currently innate_concept_datoms() in concept.rs always uses HashEmbedder (line 478). If CLI observe uses model2vec Embedder, the innate concept embeddings (hash-based) live in a different vector space from observation embeddings (model-based). Cosine similarity between different vector spaces is meaningless — this would produce WORSE results than hash-only. SOLUTION: Lazy re-embedding. On first 'braid observe' with a model embedder, detect that innate concepts have hash embeddings (store a :concept/embedder-type datom). If mismatch, re-embed innate concept descriptions with the model embedder and update the concept embedding datoms. This is a one-time migration per store that runs transparently. ALTERNATIVE: Store both hash and model embeddings for each concept. Use the one matching the current embedder. REJECTED: doubles storage, adds complexity. ALTERNATIVE: Always use hash embedder for innate concepts, lower JOIN_THRESHOLD for hash-vs-hash matches. REJECTED: defeats the purpose — the whole point is semantic similarity, not keyword overlap. VERIFICATION: (A) After re-embedding, cosine(innate_anomalies_model, observation_model) produces meaningful values. (B) Re-embedding is idempotent. (C) Hash-only stores continue to work without degradation.; MODEL-WIRE PROPOSAL: Wire Embedder into the CLI observe pipeline, replacing the hard-coded HashEmbedder. CURRENT STATE: observe.rs line 536 creates HashEmbedder unconditionally: 'let hash_embedder = HashEmbedder::new(DEFAULT_DIM); let obs_embedding = TextEmbedder::embed(&hash_embedder, args.text)'. PROPOSED STATE: The observe command receives a Box<dyn TextEmbedder> from the CLI entrypoint. The entrypoint tries to load model files; if successful, uses Embedder; otherwise HashEmbedder. The embedder is constructed ONCE at startup and shared across commands (not per-invocation). APPROACH: (1) Add an EmbedderFactory to the CLI crate that resolves the best available embedder. (2) Thread the embedder through ObserveArgs or a shared CLI context. (3) The observe command, status command, and harvest command all use the same embedder instance. (4) The innate concept datoms in init.rs should also use the model embedder when available — hash-embedded innate concepts vs model-embedded observations would have near-zero cosine. CRITICAL INVARIANT: innate concept embeddings and observation embeddings MUST use the same embedder. If init creates concepts with HashEmbedder but observe embeds with Embedder, cosine similarity is meaningless (different vector spaces). VERIFICATION: (A) When model present, cosine(innate_anomalies, 'ignored error returns') > JOIN_THRESHOLD. (B) When model absent, behavior is identical to current (hash embedder fallback). (C) Innate concepts are re-embedded on first observe if embedder type changed since init.; Session entity: :task/t-62fcc504; MODEL-LOAD PROPOSAL: The CLI needs a model management subsystem. The potion-base-8M model (30.2MB safetensors + 684KB tokenizer.json) must be downloaded to a well-known location and loaded at CLI startup when available. APPROACH: (1) Model storage location: ~/.braid/models/potion-base-8M/ containing model.safetensors and tokenizer.json. Project-local override: .braid/models/. (2) Download command: 'braid model download' fetches from HuggingFace (minishlab/potion-base-8M). No auto-download — explicit user action. (3) Loading: at CLI startup, check for model files. If present, construct Embedder::from_bytes(). If absent, fall back to HashEmbedder. The TextEmbedder trait abstraction already supports this — callers use Box<dyn TextEmbedder>. (4) C8 compliance: the kernel never does IO. Model bytes are loaded by the CLI crate and passed to the kernel's Embedder::from_bytes(). The kernel remains a pure computation library. VERIFICATION: (A) 'braid model download' creates the files in the expected location. (B) 'braid observe' uses Embedder when model present, HashEmbedder when absent. (C) Embedding dimension matches DEFAULT_DIM (256). (D) Model absence does not cause errors — graceful degradation.; Session entity: :task/t-51654d1a; Session entity: :task/t-db1d0622; THRESHOLD-TUNE PROPOSAL: The JOIN_THRESHOLD (0.65) was calibrated for hash embedder cosine distributions, not model2vec distributions. Hash embedder cosine is sparse (many zero overlaps, high values only when many words match). Model2vec cosine is dense (most texts have some similarity, values spread across [0.1, 0.9]). The threshold that separates 'same concept' from 'different concept' may need adjustment for the model embedder. APPROACH: (1) Before tuning, measure the distribution. Embed the 5 innate concept descriptions + 30 DOGFOOD-3 observations with model2vec. Compute the 5x30 cosine similarity matrix. (2) For each observation, check: does the highest-similarity innate concept match human intuition? What threshold separates correct matches from incorrect ones? (3) Expected outcome: model2vec should produce cosine > 0.5 for semantically related pairs (anomalies description vs error-handling observation) and cosine < 0.3 for unrelated pairs. The threshold may need to drop from 0.65 to 0.45-0.55 for model2vec. (4) Make threshold configurable via policy manifest: :policy/concept-join-threshold. The constant JOIN_THRESHOLD becomes the default when no policy datom exists. VERIFICATION: (A) Distribution analysis produces a clear bimodal separation. (B) Threshold produces >=80% correct concept assignment on DOGFOOD-3 observations. (C) Policy-manifest threshold override works.; GATE-RERUN PROPOSAL: After model2vec integration, re-run CCE-GATE (DOGFOOD-3) with identical protocol. Same 3 agents (Architecture Explorer, Code Review Analyst, Spec Auditor), same Go CLI codebase, same prompts, same scoring rubric. This is the empirical test of whether semantic embeddings resolve the hash embedder bottleneck. PREDICTED SCORES (with model2vec): Overall 7-8/10 (was 5.3 with hash), Connection quality 7/10 (was 4 — concept-mediated connections should fire), Discovery 7/10 (unchanged — agents are capable regardless), Orientation 7/10 (was 5 — innate schemas should match observations and guide exploration), Responsiveness 7/10 (was 4 — concept membership lines + surprise scaling + steering questions should all activate), Persistence 7/10 (was 6 — concepts formed during session are transmissible). GO/NO-GO CRITERIA: If overall >= 7/10, CCE is validated. Proceed to Phase B. If 5-6/10, semantic embeddings helped but architecture needs further work. If < 5/10, the embedding hypothesis is falsified — return to first principles. DEPENDS-ON: MODEL-LOAD, MODEL-WIRE, EMBEDDER-CONSISTENCY, THRESHOLD-TUNE." :op :assert}
